  "prompt": "What are the best residential schools from class 9 in Hyderabad / Secunderabad? With low fees",
  "response": "Finding the \"best\" residential school with low fees is tricky because \"best\" is subjective and low fees are relative. Here's a breakdown of factors to consider and some schools that might fit the bill, keeping in mind that \"low fees\" will likely mean government-run or aided schools:\n\n**Factors to Consider When Choosing a Residential School:**\n\n*   **Academic Reputation:** Check their board exam results (SSC/CBSE/ICSE) over the past few years.  Good pass rates and high averages are a good sign.\n*   **Infrastructure:**  Look for good classrooms, labs (science and computer), a library, sports facilities, and clean and well-maintained hostels.\n*   **Faculty:**  Experienced and dedicated teachers are crucial. Inquire about teacher qualifications and turnover rates.\n*   **Student-Teacher Ratio:**  A lower ratio allows for more individual attention.\n*   **Co-curricular Activities:** Look for a range of activities like sports, arts, music, debate, and clubs.\n*   **Discipline and Safety:**  A safe and disciplined environment is essential.  Inquire about rules, security measures, and anti-bullying policies.\n*   **Location:**  Consider the school's proximity to your home and accessibility.\n*   **Fees:** This is your primary concern.  Government schools and schools run by charitable trusts will typically have lower fees than private schools.\n\n**Potential Schools (with the caveat that you need to independently verify fees and availability):**\n\n*   **Telangana Social Welfare Residential Educational Institutions Society (TSWREIS) Schools:** These are government-run and offer free education, boarding, and lodging to students from disadvantaged backgrounds.  Admission is typically based on merit (entrance exam).  These would definitely be your \"low fees\" option.  Look up the TSWREIS website for information on schools in Hyderabad and their admission process.\n*   **Telangana Tribal Welfare Residential Educational Institutions Society (TTWREIS) Schools:** Similar to TSWREIS, but specifically for students from tribal communities.\n*   **Andhra Pradesh Residential Schools (APRS):** While technically in Andhra Pradesh now (after the state split), some APRS schools are located close to the Hyderabad border and might be an option if you're willing to consider that.  They are government-run and offer subsidized education.  Check their website.\n*   **Kendriya Vidyalayas (KVs) with Hostel Facilities:** Some KVs (Central Government schools) have hostel facilities.  KV fees are relatively low, but hostel fees are extra.  Admission is primarily for children of central government employees and transferable jobs, but a limited number of seats might be available for others.\n*   **Navodaya Vidyalayas (JNVs):** These are fully residential, co-educational schools run by the central government. Admission is through an entrance exam. JNVs provide free education, boarding, and lodging.\n*   **Some Private Schools Run by Trusts/Religious Organizations:** Some schools run by charitable trusts or religious organizations might offer relatively lower fees compared to purely commercial private schools.  You'll need to research these individually.  Examples (these are just starting points; you MUST verify):\n    *   Some schools run by the Ramakrishna Mission\n    *   Schools run by certain Christian missionary organizations\n\n**How to Find More Information and Verify Fees:**\n\n1.  **TSWREIS and TTWREIS Websites:** These are your best resources for government-run residential schools. Look for their school lists, admission notifications, and contact information.\n2.  **APRS Website:** Check for schools near the Hyderabad border and admission details.\n3.  **Kendriya Vidyalaya Sangathan Website (kvsangathan.nic.in):** Look for KVs in Hyderabad and inquire about hostel availability and fees.\n4.  **Navodaya Vidyalaya Samiti Website (navodaya.gov.in):** Check for nearby Navodaya Vidyalayas.\n5.  **Online School Directories:** Websites like Careers360, Shiksha.com, and EducationWorld might have listings of residential schools in Hyderabad, but be *very* careful about the information they provide, especially regarding fees.\n6.  **Directly Contact the Schools:** This is the most important step!  Call the schools you're interested in and ask about:\n    *   Fees (including tuition, boarding, lodging, and any other charges)\n    *   Admission procedure\n    *   Availability of seats in Class 9\n    *   Infrastructure and facilities\n    *   Academic performance\n    *   Contact details of current students or parents (if possible)\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Entrance Exams:** Most residential schools, especially government-run ones, have entrance exams for admission.  Prepare your child accordingly.\n*   **Syllabus:**  Make sure the school follows a syllabus (CBSE, ICSE, State Board) that your child is familiar with or is willing to adapt to.\n*   **Visit the Schools:** If possible, visit the shortlisted schools to get a feel for the environment and facilities.\n*   **Talk to Current Students/Parents:**  If you can, speak to current students or their parents to get honest feedback about the school.\n*   **Don't solely rely on online information:** Always verify information with the school directly.\n\nFinding the right residential school with low fees requires thorough research and effort. Good luck!\n",
